Any combination of shipments or deliveries can be combined onto the same load as long as they are referencing the same carrier number. Pick list numbers and could have been, and probably should have been, combined onto one shipment as they had the same shipment specification number, which meant that all infomration in the VASPEZ table was the same between the two pick lists. However, pick list number should not have been able to be combine, and it wasn't. VSS did allow it to go on the same load since all pick lists were referencing the same carrier Hi John, the question is why shouldn't we. I checked the shipments and there is no reason to deny putting them in one load. A load is principally just a carrier. You put the packages on a carrier but you don't know how far it drives. For example If you make a load for three customers, the carrier can drive to a HUB and the divide it in three different carriers. Therefore it is allowed to put them together. Greeting Stefan EDT How could VSS allow these packages shipments to be combined. John > Not sure if this was an IAS or VSS issue.

During the transition the open SAP session gets lost because the network adapter gets a new IP adress when the pc will be connected or disconnected from the docking station. That s the way it is. Other applications like Outlook mostly keep the connection because they always try to comunicate with the server or Cache mode. But also our users reports broken connections, sometimes even a bluescreen. Some of them had a defective PST, because Outlook was still open and the PST file was in active use on the server. In my opinion this is a wrong handling. They have to close all applications before they connect or disconnect their system. There s no parameter to adjust this.
